      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is a bit frightening. If we have a generic type it should actually be generic.\n\nThere are two ways to go about this. The first is to make SkText something which one could wrap in a UText. This is difficult. The second option is to not share the UText (just create two UTexts backed by the same char*).\n\nIn this second case we don\u0027t need SkText yet (though we should probably have something like it in the future which can wrap non-contiguous text input). Just have setText here create a new UText (it doesn\u0027t even need to be new\u0027ed, it could be embedded here in the type and initialized here). The UText doesn\u0027t take ownership of or make a copy of the data, so there isn\u0027t really much overhead (and less than calling \u0027new\u0027 a bunch).",
